Input.threadtitle: What triggers the reverse shock wave ?
Input.posts:
My model for imagining a returning wave is an echo that bounces back from a wall, and I do not see the 'wall' in a supernova. I understand that the whole matter of the deceased star comprises the advancing shock wave and that the wave sweeps with it interstellar matter, but where is the wall ? Why should there be a reflected wave ?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
If you haven't already, I would suggest reading the educational pages in the Week 5 Wiki under Section 5.2: Supernova Remnants. The last page references a popular way of explaining the forward and reverse shocks that take place in a supernova remnant via a comparison to traffic on the highway. I will try to elaborate on this...Following a supernova explosion, expanding ejecta drive a shock into the ambient interstellar medium (ISM). Initially, the ejecta expand almost freely and cool adiabatically, however, upon interaction with the ISM the ambient material is accelerated, compressed, and heated until the pressure of the shocked ambient material exceeds the thermal pressure of the ejecta and pushes back into the ejecta creating a reverse shock. The ISM functions as a 'wall' in this case - impeding the almost free expansion of the ejecta. As mentioned earlier, the reverse shock effect is somewhat similar to traffic build-up on a highway. The block of cars standing still up ahead resemble the ISM or the 'wall' that impedes the flow of incoming traffic. As each incoming car is forced to slow down and stop due to the blocked roadway ahead, a backwards propagating wave will form. The following video attempts to show this effect: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Suugn-p5C1M .

Initially, the ejecta expand almost freely and cool adiabatically, however, upon interaction with the ISM the ambient material is accelerated, compressed, and heated until the pressure of the shocked ambient material exceeds the thermal pressure of the ejecta and pushes back into the ejecta creating a reverse shock. The ISM functions as a 'wall' in this case - impeding the almost free expansion of the ejecta. As mentioned earlier, the reverse shock effect is somewhat similar to traffic build-up on a highway. The block of cars standing still up ahead resemble the ISM or the 'wall' that impedes the flow of incoming traffic. As each incoming car is forced to slow down and stop due to the blocked roadway ahead, a backwards propagating wave will form. Input.posts:
I find it difficult to understand how a nearly massless neutrino, very difficult even to detect on the earth, could be responsible for the final shock wave during a supernova explosion. Billions of neutrinos pass through the earth every second and we hardly detect their presence.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
It is hard to imagine, but there are few things that affect this. One is that the density of the neutrinos is quite high, so instead of merely billions of neutrinos per second, we have.... well, you can calculate this based on the quiz! What the neutrino lacks in interaction cross-section, it makes up for in the sheer numbers that are produced in such a short time. In fact, the matter density is so high in the beginning of the core collapse that only neutrinos can escape. Of these, a small percentage of them are absorbed by the stalled shock. This is what we think starts the true 'explosion'. But you are correct in that the details of this mechanism are far from being completely understood.

Title: Linking forum posts - analyze-7-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
Fascinating lectures this week. I have a question or two about the relation of pulsars/neutron stars to that of quasars. The physical mechanisms (I'm likely oversimplifying here) for each seem quite similar. Both are characterized by extremely high densities (or at least very small in size), funneling of accretion material via magnetic fields, their close connection to black holes, and the 'lighthouse' effect. The main differentiating characteristic, to me at least, is the scale on which these occur, and rather than supernovae, quasars simply fuel an ongoing explosion via the SMBH. So does a pulsar's processes serve as a model (microscopic in scale) for the quasar? Additionally, a question raised in one of the wiki entries is 'most galaxies in our cosmic neighbourhood, including the Milky Way, appear to have a dormant black hole which is not funnelling in large amounts of matter at present.' Could it be due to simply not enough matter in our cluster/galaxy, or that we just haven't yet been able to accurately measure the Milky Way from the different perspectives required of a galactic center (even though it isn't an AGN)? I'm curious to hear thoughts, speculations, etc.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
The pulsars were a mystery more easily unraveled than the quasars. Our knowledge of what goes on in neutron stars is much more extensive than the dynamics of black holes. But in general, you are right; similar processes are going on in both types of objects. I think the biggest difference is in the evolutionary behavior of the two types. We more or less understand how neutron stars occur, but how quasars evolve is still in a primitive state. And that is part of the problem with your second query. It is clear that galaxy evolution is a complicated business. It is likely that the Milky Way was once a more active entity. It's not that we can't see it; if it were emitting even a small fraction of the radiation of 3C 273, we would know about it. So the story is fairly complicated, as usual, and enough questions remain to employ a lot of us in universities!

Input.posts:
I'm totally lost on the estimation of the energy output from the quasar. How is the potential energy of a body relevant here ? If the body is attracted by a gravittional field, then it will lose potential energy, and gain kinetic energy. Once it moves beyond the Schwartschild radius, any energy it emits will never leave that radius. The energy we see from a black hole is the energy emitted by bodies being torn apart before they reach the Sradius, so the potential energy seems irrelevant here. Also, I understand the '1 solar mass' and '1 year' to be picked at random to end up with a value that more or less matches what we see from the quasar, to give a rough comparison. There's no deeper significance there, right ? Thanks
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
All energy must be accounted for. If you lose potential energy, it can (and must) appear elsewhere. So before any material gets to the Schwarzschild radius, if it loses potential energy, it may convert that energy into radiation. It turns out that gravity is pretty good at doing this, so potential energy can be important.

So before any material gets to the Schwarzschild radius, if it loses potential energy, it may convert that energy into radiation. It turns out that gravity is pretty good at doing this, so potential energy can be important.
